  "prompt": "Is white an actual color?",
  "response": "The classification of white as a color can depend on the context in which it\u2019s being discussed. \n\nIn terms of physics and light, white is considered the presence of all colors in the light spectrum. When light is refracted, it can be dispersed into a range of colors, and combining all those colors of light results in white light. This is why a prism can separate white light into a rainbow of colors.\n\nIn the context of pigment and paint, white is typically seen as the absence of color. When mixing paint, colors tend to absorb specific wavelengths of light. White pigment generally reflects most wavelengths and is considered to be a neutral or achromatic color. \n\nSo, while white can be classified as a color in terms of light, it can be viewed differently in terms of pigment and painting. Ultimately, whether white is considered a color can depend on the specific context.",
